{"/service/ndnp/wyu/batch_wyu_karig_ver02/data/sn92067163/00542862129/1924030701/0149.xml":{"full_text":"FEDERAL ESTIMATE OF\nWEAITHOF WYOMING\nIn a special bulletin, issued March\n8, the Department of Commerce an\nnounces, for the State of Wyoming,\nits preliminary estimate of the value,\nDecember 31, 1922, of the principal\nforma of wealth, the total amounting\nto $976,239,000, as compared with\n0358,139,000 in 1912, an increase of\n177.2 per cent Per capita values in\ncreased from 02,230 to $4,663, or\n109.1 per cent.\nAll classes of property increased\nin value from 1912 to 1922, except\nprivately owned transporation and\ntransmission enterprises, other than\nrailroads, which decreased from $26,-\n724,000 to 025,039,000, or 6.3 per cent.\nThe estimated value of taxed real\nproperty and improvements increased\nfrom 081,270,000 to 0263,216,000 or\n223.9 per c#nt; exempt real property\n(exclusive of Yellowstone National\nPark and Devil\u2019s Tower National\nMonument) from 09,010,000 to $326,-\n530,000, or 3,524.1 per cent; live stock\nfrom 154,435,000 to 059,682,000, or 9.6\nper cent; farm implements and ma\nehiaary, from 04,129.000 to $8,624,-\n000, or 108.9 per cent; maunfacturing\nmachinery, tools, and implements\nfrom 03,044,000 to 028,410,000, or\n833.3 per cent; and railroads and their\nequipment from 0104,966,000 to\n0128,700,000, or 22.6 per cent. Stocks\nof goods, vehicles other than motor,\nfurniture, and clothing increased in\nvalue from 068,561,000 to $124,641,-\n000, or 81.8 per cent. No comparison\nis possible for the value of motor ve\nhicles, which was estimated in 1922 at\n011,397,000, because no separate esti\nmate was made in 1912.\nIn making these estimates the de\npartment followed in general the\nmethods employed in making the esti\nmates for 1912, though it is believed\nthat in some respects the work in\n1922 has been more thorough. It\nshould be borne in mind that the in\ncreases in money value are to a large\nFor\n\u201cThat Well Dressed Look\u201d\nA Wooltex Outfit\nSuit \u2014Coat \u2014Dress\nSA (fw\nv 1,11\ni J lllllll\nI ilium h n, w'\nI V'l\u0964in \u2014W\u2014\nI 11111111\nI nun 'I M\niimi A y k Mu\nL jnm W rX\nlimn f Zhi\nI yimi /RAI\nJ\u2014 Jmi\nSuits\nIf you (Io not possess a suit, then indeed is this\nthe season to buy one. In Wooltex you will find both\nthe longer and shorter length coat, the latter most\npopular with the small woman and young girl. In\nfabrics you ean select Poiret Twill or the outdoor\nmaterials in stripes, plaids and plain colors.\n$35.00 to $65.00\nCoats\nIn spring one must have a coat. Our showing in\ncludes dress coats that follow the popular tube\nsilhoutte, tailored in finest Poiret Twill; others for all\noccasion wear in soft fleecy materials, downy wools;\nand a most interesting group of topcoats in plaids,\nstripes and plain polaires. The Wooltex label appears\nin every one. Priced\n$25.00 to $75.00\nDreues\nTo complete your Wooltex wardrobe there are\ndresses of two types\u2014the smart flannel sport dress\nfor every day and country club wear and the silk frock\nin a beautiful crepe for more dress occasions. Priced\n$16.50 to $55.00\nBlyth-Fargo-Hoskins Co.\nThe store that sells Wooltex\nextent due to the rise in prices which\nhss taken place in recent yean, and\nso far as that is the case they do not\nrepresent corresponding increases in\nthe quantity of wealth.\nSILVER TROTHY FOR\nLIVE STOCK EXHIBIT\nLincoln county will have an oppor\ntunity to compete for a sterling silver\ncup which will be offered by a Salt\nLake newspaper for the best and most\ndiversified exhibit of live stock at the\nIntermountain Stock Show to be held\nin Salt Lake April 1 to 5.\nCompetition for this cup is limited\nto the intermountain country and is\nfor live stock adapted to this section.\nCounties in Utah, Nevada,, Idaho,\nMontana and Wyoming may enter.\nAside from the .prize itself, which is\nsaid to be a magnificent one, the ad\nvertising feature for the section win\nning the cup will be of great value\nand it would apear that this county\nshould have a good chance to bring\nhome the cup.\nSYNTHETIC GRANITE\nAn exchange says that they are\nmaking stuff harder than synthetic\ngin. Government chemists have dis\ncovered how to make granite synthe\ntically\u2014turn it out in the laboratory\nin car load lots. Granite is the hard\nest and most enduring of Dame Na\nture\u2019s rocky creations and it has\ntaken aeons in the making. Now the\nprofessors can take a concrete mixer,\na salt spoon and the ace of spades\nand run out a mess of granite as big\nas Cheops\u2019s pyramid. It would seem\nthat there was something to hold the\nattention of the road builders. If we\ncan have laboratory granite flowing\nover our highways we might be able\nto get a surface that would even\nbother a gasman to pick to pieces. It\nis worth looking into, at any rate. We\nare weary of paying for roads that\nwill not stand up under a wheelbar\nrow load of German marks.\nSubscribe for The Republican\nTHE KEMMERER REPUBLICAN, FRIDAY. MARCH 7, 1924\nINDUSTRIAL REVIVAL\nSHOWN TO_BE GENERAL\nDovetailing into one another and\nforming a large contributing factor in\nthe present business, financial and in\ndustrial activities and the prosperity\nwhich has marked a new era in the\neconomic history of the country,\nbuilding operations, railroad improve\nments, certain agricultural produc\ntion and steel output aggregate an\nenoromous sum, unpreccnted in the\nannals of business. Somb figures\npresented by the National Cjty bank\nof New York are of unusual interest.\nOne of the greatest factors in the\nindustrial revival f roni'YU beginning\nin 1922,' thdl\u00abnlf*s' statistician notes;\nhas been the amount of building con\nstruction under way, the explanation\nof which may be found in the restric\ntion of such work during the war and\nthe high costs immediately following.\nA survey of the Copper and Brass Re\nsearch association shows that in 1923\nthe total amount of building activi\nties of all classes was $5,922,900,000.\nNext to house-building operations,\nthe railroads were the largest factor\nin the business revival of last year.\nIt is estimated that the railroads used\ntwenty-seven per cent of the steel\nmanufactured, the total capital ex\npenditures being about $1,076,000,000.\nWhile it is not probable that the ex\npenditures for 1924 will total such a\nhuge amount, some railroads have al\nready announced programs that have\nbeen definitely adopted and which\ncall for a total of approximately\n$243,000,000.\nThe unusual demand for steel has\nresulted in a great expansion of this\nindustry, and a number of plants have\nbeen enlarged, despite the statement\nof two years ago that this industry\nhad been expanded beyond probable\nneeds of ten years or more. The\nUnited States Steel Corporation has\nplanned for 1924 capital expenditures\nof $15,000,000. The prices of grains\nare higher. Large crops were the\nrule and the steady demand has had a\ntendency to keep the prices firm. Last\nyear was a record one for hog produc\ntion.\nHydro-electric development is re\nported as unprecedented. More than\n$700,000,000 of new capital was in\nvested last year for additions to\nsteam and hydro-electric plants, trans\nmission lines and the general equip\nment of distribution, while the total\ninvestment in the central stations of\nthe country is now nearly six billions.\nElectric energy is one of the few cost\nof-living items that is lower than in\n1913, and this is suggestive of other\ndevelopments under way.\nEverything considered, this country\nis jogging along at a safe pace that\ncan be kept up for a longer period\nthan if engaged in a spurt which\nwould soon necessitate slowing up.\nCaution is the watchword, and seldom\nhas there been such an absence of the\nspeculative element.\nMrs. A. M. King was the hostess to\nthe Bridge club on Saturday. The\ndecorations in\u201ethe home and menu\nwere suggestive of St. Patrick\u2019s. The\nprize for the highest score was pre\nsented to Mrs. Stanley Wagner. Tho\ndelicious lunch served by the hostess\nCompleted the pleasant afternoon.\nMrs. Stanley Wagner was the hos\nteas to the Homo Economics club\nWednesday. After the business was\ncompleted a social evening was spent\nwith games and music. A dainty\nI lunch was served.\nThe dance given by the members of\nthe R. P. C. club was a complete suc\ncess. A most enjoyable evening was\nspent in dancing and a tempting\nlunch was served at 12 o'clock.\nMr. P. Bergman is visiting relatives\nthis week.\nW FONTANELLE\nMr. and Mrs. David Alplanalp made\na trip to Kemmerer last week.\nWilliam Jameson called at Ned\nHerschler\u2019s last Sunday.\nMrs. Joe Herschler has returned to\nthe ranch on Fontenelle after spend\ning a few weeks in Ogden and Salt\nLake,\nNorris Griggs visited nt Clarence\nHolden's and Jack Walters\u2019 Sunday\nand Monday.\nMisses Ruth and Ruby Danvers are\nvisiting at the Hamp home. They an'\nthe nieces of Mr. and Mrs. Hump.\nMrs. William Danvers has been ill\nthe last few days.\nDorris Wicklzer. Marian ami Joella\nI Holden were Sunday visitors at Algot\nLarson's.\n1\nIsm Stopp has made his annual\ntrip of assessing on Fontenelle.\n'\u2022NUMBER PLEASE\"\nTho first womnn telephone operator\nIs still on the Job. She wss taken\nwhen the exchange in Now York City\nwas opened in 1878 and Is even now\nanswering a switchboard at a subur\nban station over the river In New\nJersey, Her name was Mary Ken\nnedy when she started and she dings\n\u0964to It still. Before her day only men\n1 were In the telephone service, but the\nNew York exchange desired to hove\nsomebody on the wire who wouldn't\nswoar and fight with the subscribers.\nThe suggestion was made to try a\nI girl\u2014and Mary was IL She Is on\n1 watch yet and several millions of her\nyounger sisters have gone through\ni the mill since she paved the way.\nWithout women the telephone service\niof America could not run an hour.\nLOCAL BOXER MAKES\nVERY GOOD SHOWING\nIN SALT LAKE CITY\nFight fans from Cumberland to\nSublet are interested in the outcome\nof the six-round scrap in which the\nlocal favorite Johnny Gibbs appeared\nin Salt Lake Tuesday night, when he\nwas pitted against Herman Auerbach,\nwho stands ace high with the ring fol\nlowers of the Utah capital. A Salt\nLake paper has tho following account\nof the match, which is distinctly\ncreditable to Gibbs:\n\u201cThe six-round bout last night at\nthe Hippodrome theatre between Her\nman Auerbach and Johnny Gibbs\nended with the refree\u2019s calling all\nhonors even.\n\u201cHerman can feel exceptionally\nlucky at th is* \"decision, for Gibbs cer\ntainly punished the local boy in the\nlast five rounds. The third and fifth\nespecially did the Wyoming junior\nwelter push over some wicked right\ncrosses flush to the face, each one\nleaving a good mark.\n\u201cHerman featured his usual aggres\nsiveness and some hard uppercuts\nwhile in clinches.\n\u201cIn the third round Gibbs landed al\nmost every blow and staggered Her\nman to the ropes with a solid right\ncross to the nose. Again in the fifth\nhe turned Auerbach completely around\nwith a right to the head.\n\u201cGibbs tired somewhat in the final\nround, while Herman worked fast to\nregain lost honors. The bout was\ngood.\u201d\nST. PATRICK\u2019S CHURCH\nThe members of St. Patrick\u2019s church\nwill begin the Forty Hours\u2019 Devotion\nnext Sunday morning at the 9 o\u2019clock\nmass. This devotion will be carried\nover Monday and will close Tuesday\nevening. The following is the pro\ngram of services for the three days:\nSunday: High Mass at 9 o\u2019clock and\nsermon by Father Szymanski.\nBenediction at 7:30 p. m and\nsermon by Rev. Anton Schiffrer\nof Rock Springs.\nMonday: Masses at 7:30 and 8:00 a.m.\nHoly Hour at 7:30 p. m. and ser\nmon by Rev. Henry Schellinger\nof Green River.\nTuesday: Masses at 7:00, 7:30 and\n8:00 a. m.\nClosing devotions at 7:30 p. m.\nand sermon by Rev. Sylvester A.\nWelsh of Rock Springs.\nMETHODIST CHURCH\nT. H. Evans, Pastor\nSunday school at 10 o\u2019clock. The\nnew Sunday school books will be used\ndedicated and then used at this ser\nvice. Morning worship at 11 a. m.\nTopic, \u201cThe Importance of Lent;\u201d\nBrotherhood club will meet at the\nchurch at 2:30 p. m., non-sectarian\u2014\nall men and boys invited to attend.\nEpworth League at 6:30. Leader,\nMiss Virginia Fraser. Evening wor\nship at 7:30. Subject, \u201cBrotherhood,\u201d\nmusic by senior choir. Cheer up!\nWhen down in the mouth, think of\nJonah; he came out all right.\nDEEDS AND PATENTS\nOF RECENT FILINGS\nPatentH\nJune 29, 1920\u2014U. S. A. by Wood\nrow Wilson, President, to David W.\nSalmon, S 34, T 23, R 116.\nSept. 20, 1922\u2014U. S. A. by Warren\nG. Harding, President, to John J.\nFluckiger, S 9, T 33, R 118.\nNOT IN KEMMERER\nIs bobbed hair going out of style?\nGood gracious no! Florence Beach,\nEthel Platt, Pauline Parent, Venna\nGray, Helen Mason, Mildred and\nMary Mosby, and Vera Payne have\nbeen added to the bobbed hair list,\nsince the last report was given. It\nsurely would not take long now to\nname the girls of K. H. S. who haven\u2019t\ntheir hair bobbed.\u2014Le Petit Ranger.\nGREAT WATERWAY PROJECT\nThe Canadian government has indi\ncated its willingness to co-operate\nwith the United States in investigat\ning the feasibility of improving the\ni St. Ixiwrcnce river so ns to make\npossible deepwater navigation be\ntween Montreal und the Great Lakes.\nOpposition to the St. Ijiwrvnce project\nappears to be dwindling, not only in\nCanada but in certain sections of this\ncountry, and It seems assured that the\nfuture will witness its completion.\nStates of the Middle West which have\ntaken the lend in urging tho improve\nment are indebted to the state depart\nment for Its able conduct of the m go\ntintions with Canudn.\nLISTEN. MR. McADOO\nEvery person old enough to under\nstand the ways of human nature und\nbrute nature will appreciate the ap\npropriateness of tho illustration used\nb\\ Mr. Doheny when he described his\ndog, in pioneer days, joining tho puck\nof wolvoa to yelp around his cubin.\nMr. Doheny remarked that he thought\nhe could hoar th\u00ab* voices of some of\nhis \u201cfriends\u2019\u2019 in the pack now yelping\nnt him. Wo hope Mr. McAdoo can\ntake a hint.\nA LAMBING RECORD\nRay Densley, of Nounan, who Is\nconnected with H. 8. Urano in tho\nrhoep business, was in from the\nCrane ranch in Nounan on Saturday,\nand brought the news that tho Crane\ncompany are experiencing exceeding\nI good luck with their flock this spring,\nand that lambing will exceed 100 per\ncent. Lambing was about over with\none big flock, said Mr. Densley,\ni limbing one hundred and fifty per\ncent Is nn exceptional record. This\nmoans that there are three lambs to\nevery two eyea,\u2014Montpelier Kx\nnminer.\nThere Is so much \u201cStop, thief!\u201d out\ncry In Washington that it is not\nstranire that people would want to\ntake a look at those who art doing the\nyellinf.\u2014Houston Post\nA very successful dance was given\nat the Community hall by Miss Lane\nour teacher, on February 23rd.\nMr. and Mrs. Murk Twiehel were\nguests of Mr. and Mrs. Frank Mc-\nGinnis last Sunday.\nMiss Luella Bloom, teacher at Viola,\nhas been sick with the flu, the past\nweek.\nMiss Lane spent this week-end at\nthe Oliver Twiehel home.\nWe Have Every\nthing for the Farm\nand Ranch\nGROCERIES, DRY GOODS,\nBOOTS AND SHOES\nGREEN RIVER VALLEY PEOPLE: Outfit at nearest\nRailroad Point. Save hauling expense and get goods\nat lowest market prices.\nWrite or Telephone Us for Prices\nPrompt Attention Given all Mail\nOrders\nOPAL MERC. CO. Inc.\nDealers in\u2014\u2014\nGeneral Merchandise\nOPAL, WYOMING\nFresh Pies, Bread and Cake\nALL KINDS BEST PASTRY\nFresh Every Day\nFRESH POPCORN DELICIOUS CREAMPUFFS\nTHE CITY HOME BAKERY\nKEMMERER, WYOMING\nLet Us Worry About\nYOUR FOOD!\nWhy Ixither with perplexing kitchen problems, when\nwe gladly assume them for you? Home-cooked foods in\nsplendid assortments are featured on our Menus. Dishes\nare prepared as you would have them in your own home.\nKEMMERER HOTEL CAFE\nKemmerer, Wyoming\nCome in nnd Hear the Famous Wurlitser Orchestra Piano\nKemmerer Soda Bottling Factory\nManufacturers of\nCoco-Cola. Ginger Ale. Bottled Sodas, and Seller Water\nFOR A COOL, REFRESHING DRINK\nYOU WILL FIND NOTHING BETTER\nERNEST W. HOLMES. Prop. KEMMERER, WTO.\nPAGE THREE\nMr. Ed Willey was a caller at Viola\ntoday.\nMrs. N. H. Whitman spent Satur\nday afternoon with his daughter, Mrs.\nGenetti.\nA little snow storm on upper La\nBarge te past week has enabled the\nranchers to feed their cattle on sleighs\nagain.\nMr. and Mrs. Oscar Henderson left\nThursday for a trip up tho river\nwhere they will visit their daughter,\nMrs. Jack McClellan.\nPhil Twiehel and son Mark made a\ntrip to the oil wells today.","height":"21252","width":"15140"}}
